"Abstract Public Key (PK) cryptography has been hailed by many as the Holy Grail of Internet security, providing trusted third parties to authenticate the identity of those online. However, while this may sound good in principle, it is unworkable in practise. Here, Tim Charrot, security architect at Internet security consultancy @stake, looks at the demand for PK and some of the problems associated with it. He concludes that, as ever, perfect security is simply a myth and encourages those seeking to implement secure sites to take a close look at the risks involved and make some hard decisions about which of them can be prevented and which should simply be borne."
